# =============================================================================
# The Drain Man — environment variables
# =============================================================================
# Copy this file to `.env.local` for local development, and set the same keys in
# your host's dashboard for production (e.g. Vercel → Settings → Environment
# Variables):
#
#     cp .env.example .env.local
#
# `.env.local` is gitignored — never commit real keys. Only this template (with
# placeholder values) is tracked.
#
# A note on prefixes:
#   • NEXT_PUBLIC_*  → inlined into the browser bundle AT BUILD TIME. Set it
#                      before `npm run build`; changing it requires a rebuild.
#   • everything else → read on the server at request time, never exposed to the
#                       browser. Safe for secrets.
#
# Good news: the site runs with NONE of these set (sensible fallbacks are built
# in). They exist so you can point the site at your real domain and make the
# contact form actually deliver leads before launch.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------


# ── Site URL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# What it is:  the canonical, fully-qualified base URL of the live site, with NO
#              trailing slash (e.g. https://www.thedrainman.ca).
# What it does: feeds the <link rel="canonical"> / Open Graph tags
#              (metadataBase), sitemap.xml, robots.txt, and the LocalBusiness /
#              Service JSON-LD. Getting it right matters for SEO and for how
#              shared links preview on Google / social.
# How to get it: it's just your production domain — use the exact scheme + host
#              you actually serve from (https, and the www / non-www form you've
#              picked as canonical).
# Required?    No — defaults to https://www.thedrainman.ca if unset. Set it once
#              you know the final domain. (Build-time: rebuild after changing.)
NEXT_PUBLIC_SITE_URL="https://www.thedrainman.ca"


# ── Contact form delivery ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The /contact estimate form POSTs to the /api/contact route, which delivers the
# lead using whichever ONE of the options below is configured, checked in order:
#     1) CONTACT_WEBHOOK_URL   2) RESEND_API_KEY (+ CONTACT_TO_EMAIL)
# If NEITHER is set, the form still works — the lead is written to the server
# logs and the visitor still sees the success message. Wire up ONE of the two
# options before launch so real estimate requests reach the shop.
# All four below are server-only secrets — do NOT add a NEXT_PUBLIC_ prefix.

# OPTION 1 — Webhook (recommended; zero extra dependencies)
#   What it is:  a URL the lead is POSTed to as JSON.
#   What it does: lets you route leads into Zapier / Make / n8n, a CRM intake
#                hook, or a Slack / Discord "Incoming Webhook" (so the office
#                gets a ping or an email automatically). Takes priority over
#                Resend if both are set.
#   How to get it: create a Zap/Scenario (or a Slack "Incoming Webhook") and copy
#                the webhook URL it gives you.
#   Required?    No (but set this OR the Resend keys before launch).
CONTACT_WEBHOOK_URL=""

# OPTION 2 — Email via Resend (https://resend.com)
#   RESEND_API_KEY
#     What it is:  your Resend API key (starts with "re_").
#     What it does: the route emails each lead via Resend's HTTP API (no npm
#                  package needed). Used only when CONTACT_WEBHOOK_URL is unset.
#     How to get it: sign up at resend.com → Dashboard → API Keys → Create.
#     Required?    No (only if you choose the email option).
RESEND_API_KEY=""

#   CONTACT_TO_EMAIL
#     What it is:  the inbox that should receive estimate requests (the office).
#     What it does: the "to" address on the lead emails.
#     How to get it: just use the shop's monitored email address.
#     Required?    No — falls back to the site's published email if unset.
CONTACT_TO_EMAIL="office@thedrainman.ca"

#   CONTACT_FROM_EMAIL
#     What it is:  the "from" address on the lead emails.
#     What it does: who the email appears to come from.
#     How to get it: MUST be an address on a domain you've verified in Resend
#                  (Dashboard → Domains). Until your domain is verified, leave it
#                  unset — it defaults to Resend's sandbox sender
#                  (onboarding@resend.dev), which is fine for testing only.
#     Required?    No.
CONTACT_FROM_EMAIL="website@thedrainman.ca"
